comment:
Ever realise this might be the last time you hear this song, see a friend, go to a certain place?
I always had a brilliant memory - as if the distant past had just happened, I'd just been in the moment, and it would be absurd to not remember. Lately though, I've been ill and my mind is foggy. I'm having trouble concentrating. For the first time ever, I had trouble recalling details from my childhood today. Things, places, and people that were key parts of my life, that I thought I would never forget. It suddenly dawned on me that it's faded. You're so used to something and then suddenly 10/15/20/+ years have passed and you don't even know you've forgotten it unless you see or hear it again. Appreciate what you have and don't be careless with the things you want to stay in your life.

comment: Greatest song of 1989, close to when I graduated. Sounds like it did then, but not. It‚Äôs because I‚Äôve changed in 31 years. Thoughts and everything are different as to then. Seem to be going through a phase that I‚Äôm playing this song almost endlessly since I moved out of my apartment and am temporarily living at my brother‚Äôs house. Something is so interesting about it, and my 30 years of thoughts and memories , plus those then. I think this is half the reason I like this song. It‚Äôs like a ‚ÄúThen And Now‚Äù, or ‚Äú30 years Later‚Äù song. The other half is one ‚òùÔ∏è feeling my body seems to keep feeling since I threw away my thyroid medication for a simple fix I found out on YouTube.  This song explains what that feeling is, along with being twenty pounds skinnier and full of energy. Not groggy or sapped energy. All in the last couple weeks, this song hits #1 on my own top charts. Thank God for IPhones, since you can customize your own arrangement of songs. No waiting for sheer luck as to when the radio‚Äôs going to play it. Can create a 1950‚Äôs and 1960‚Äôs oldies like night. Sock hops and Doo Wop fun as well, as if going back to the time of these songs. Keep these great üëç songs coming. Even songs from 1989 to now are of interest. There‚Äôs also something interesting with Neil Young‚Äôs ‚ÄúOld Man‚Äù, heard on a wooden Crosley cathedral shaped radio I received for Christmas üéÑ of 1988. It had a lighted dial and black numbers for AM and FM. Like taking a trip back in time to 1972. A song which was only 16 years old in 1988, is now 48 years old in 2020. Man, where has the time gone!! Graduation üë©‚Äçüéì and all the memories. We will like these songs forever. I was 19 when I graduated in 1989. Hard to believe I‚Äôm turning 50 in June. Hard for my parents too, which live in Alaska. Came here to Arizona to live with my mom and stepfather. That was my graduation üë©‚Äçüéì present I was hoping to pursue when I was just 8. These songs will live forever in our thoughts, actions, memories and so on. Love üíï ‚Äúem all. They‚Äôre also decent and simple sing alongs of our childhood.

comment: I think the 1980's, as a time period in music history, faded away on the heels of this single and this album.  I don't think it is unfair to say that this single was the last true 1980's single, The Raw and the Cooked was the last true 1980's hit album, making the Fine Young Cannibals the last true 1980's act.  All the innovations and characteristics of the 1980's sound can be found in this single: the use of digital tools to create rhythm and interest, highly stylized and refined vocals, and precisely timed syncopation between the elements.  It is as if the whole of the 1980's was refined and coalesced into THIS single, to the point that, once heard, there was nowhere else for the 1980's to go.  From this time forward, the things that made this single work were no longer RAW, but COOKED, and the new rawness came from abandoning the things that made this single work (an abandonment of digital tools, an abandonment of polished vocals, and an abandonment of clean syncopation).  Enter grunge and alternative, with one last swan song to remember the 80's by.

comment: I was an American living in Germany.  I started to date a German guy.  Every single time we were in the car, this song came on.  He mentioned that one night, and it became "our song",   Now every time I hear this song, I think about that simpler life, when we, in the western world, were a whole lot more optimistic, and more friendly to each other than we are now.  I wish it was possible to go back to those times - it was such a different feeling all over - and one that I'm afraid we'll never get back.
